The key is injecting the W3C `traceparent`/`tracestate` headers on publish and extracting them on consume. Here's the pattern:

**Publisher (Service A)** — inject current context into message headers:

```csharp
using System.Diagnostics;

var activitySource = new ActivitySource("ServiceA");
using var activity = activitySource.StartActivity("PublishOrderEvent", ActivityKind.Producer);

var props = channel.CreateBasicProperties();
props.Headers = new Dictionary<string, object>();

// Inject W3C trace context
if (Activity.Current != null)
{
    props.Headers["traceparent"] = Activity.Current.Id;
    props.Headers["tracestate"] = Activity.Current.TraceStateString ?? "";
}

channel.BasicPublish(exchange, routingKey, props, body);
```

**Consumer (Service B)** — extract and link the context:

```csharp
var activitySource = new ActivitySource("ServiceB");

consumer.Received += (sender, ea) =>
{
    ActivityContext parentCtx = default;

    if (ea.BasicProperties.Headers != null
        && ea.BasicProperties.Headers.TryGetValue("traceparent", out var raw))
    {
        var traceparent = Encoding.UTF8.GetString((byte[])raw);
        ActivityContext.TryParse(traceparent, null, out parentCtx);
    }

    using var activity = activitySource.StartActivity(
        "ConsumeOrderEvent",
        ActivityKind.Consumer,
        parentCtx);          // ← links this span to the producer's trace

    // process message...
};
```

**Wire it up in `Program.cs`** for both services:

```csharp
builder.Services.AddOpenTelemetry()
    .WithTracing(t => t
        .AddSource("ServiceA")   // or "ServiceB"
        .AddAspNetCoreInstrumentation()
        .AddOtlpExporter());
```

**Why this works:** `Activity.Current.Id` is the W3C `traceparent` string (e.g. `00-<traceId>-<spanId>-01`). Passing it as a header and parsing it on the consumer side re-parents the consumer span under the same trace ID. Your backend (Jaeger, Zipkin, etc.) then stitches them into one end-to-end trace.

**If you use MassTransit or NServiceBus**, they do this automatically — no manual header work needed. The manual approach above is for raw `RabbitMQ.Client` usage.
